<Author>undome
<Content>Location, location, location Me, my mom and sister stayed for 6 nights at Duc de la Victoria in the end of August 2008. We booked the room for 3 people for a very reasonable price through the hotel's own web-site.We arrived late on Saturday evening to Barcelona airport, took the Aerobus to Placa de Catalunya (about 30 mins) and found our way to the hotel easily in some 5 minutes. I would really recommend using the bus to get here, it only costs 4,05 鈧?per adult and runs in every 10-15 minutes. The hotel's address is Duc de la Victoria, but the street sign actually reads Carrer del Duc.Check-in was quick, no problems there. The corridors of the hotel had a very pleasant smell of peach, a nice touch I think. Our room was on the 1st floor. It was spacious, nicely decorated and had a small balcony overlooking a pedestrian street. Bathroom was nice and clean with a bathtub and lovely selection of hotel's own bath products. They had even left us 2 boxes of Smints, which my mom loved.The hotel has the perfect location for perusing Barcelona. It's in Barri Gotico, surrounded by pedestrian streets, just a stone's throw away from La Rambla. One can find plenty of good restaurants and shops nearby, but I'll get to that later.We slept very good every night, the streets are surprisingly quiet as there are no cars. The room also had a good air-conditioning unit. Beds were more comfortable that I am used to expecting from European hotels. Even the extra-bed was good.We had breakfast every morning at the hotel's restaurant. Now, it wasn't included in our room price, so it was a bit pricey. But the selection and quality was unbelievable! I don't usually eat at the hotel breakfasts when I travel, but my mom does and even she was impressed with this one. You could definitely get your money's worth from the buffet, if you are a big eater. We really aren't, so maybe the price was still too high for what we ate, but the convenience of eating at the hotel made up for it. I recommend the raspberry juice, mushrooms and the juiciest watermelons I have ever had!The room had a mini-bar, which had surprisingly reasonable prices. We didn't use it though, just bought some beverages from mini-markets and brought them back to the room. There was also an option to order room-service from a local pizza-chain (again amazingly low cost), which was a fun touch.My only complaint of the hotel, aside from the price of the breakfast, would be that the maids changed the towels every day, even though we had hung them up (a sign that we can use them again). I consider myself environmentally conscious, so this bothered me a bit.Now, a few words of restaurants. There is an absolutely great place just around the corner of the hotel. From the main entrance take 2 rights and you can see the restaurant Living Barcelona. It looks a bit touristy, and most people we saw eating spoke something else than Catalan, but the food is so worth it. We had a lovely waitress, who remembered us even when we went back 2 nights after for our last evening dinner. Order the paella. On the other hand, if you want an original experience, not necessarily traditional but nice anyway, try Juicy Jones (don't remember the address, but it's mentioned in the restaurant reviews on TripAdvisor). The menu they serve is totally vegan, amazingly cheap (8,50 鈧?for 3 courses) and delicious. Even my carnivore mom liked it.All in all, Barcelona surpassed all my expectations. It is a welcoming city with charming people and brilliant art and architecture. I recommend taking the bus tour of the city (a bit touristy, yes, but you get to see all and hear interesting facts). The hotel is great, I will definitely go back and recommend to all. 
